abstract: A case illustrating the extreme exactness of the law, recently occurred at Milwaukee. A suit having been commenced before a Justice in Milwaukee, was removed by affidavit to the nearest justice under the law. The offices of the two ministers of the law were at about equal distance, and resort was had to a surveyor's chain, to ascertain which was nearest. One was found to be nine links nearer than the other.

YALE, demanded $18 per month, instead of $15, the old rate, threatening to quit him in a body, unless the demand was complied with.

abstract: FATAL ACCIDENTS.-A man named MILES GILLEROY was conveyed to the Hospital, at Flatbush, in ill health. On Saturday night, it is supposed that he walked in the corridor to the end window, and, through weakness, lost his balance, and fell to the ground, where he was found dead the next morning. Coroner BALL yesterday held an inquest, and a suitable verdict was rendered.

abstract: In all relations to the fair sex, the American gentleman is one of the most gallant of mankind. abstract: THE HAIL STORM.--The hail storm of Monday afternoon extended to Manchester, N. H., breaking glass and doing much damage. The Mirror says that some of the stones were as large as common red cherries. It is calculated that nearly 4,000 panes of glass were broken out of all the mills and the boarding-houses connected with them, in that city, to say nothing of the injury done to private residences and gardens.

abstract: One of the greatest curiosities which ever greeted a traveler's optics, is the Quaker driving around Philadelphia. abstract: Three mortal columns of the National Intelligencer this morning, are occupied by Mr. PRYOR, of the Union editorial Corps, in a labored defence of his Russian article. The Union, however, maintains its silence, and Mr. PRYOR continues his connection with it, while he seeks elsewhere a medium for the reiteration and defence of the objectionable sentiments.
